Emerging Stocks Fall, Led by China Companies

-- B y   W e i y i   L i m   a n d   J a s o n   W e b b
-- 
2011-10-03T11:19:55Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-10-03/emerging-stocks-fall-led-by-china-companies.html
Emerging stocks extended losses after
completing the worst quarterly drop since 2008 amid mounting
concern there will be a world economic slowdown and European
leaders prepared to weigh the risk of a Greek default.  The MSCI Emerging Markets Index sank 2.6 percent to 857.75
at 12:02 p.m. in  London , following its 23 percent plunge in the
three months ended Sept. 30. The Hang Seng China Enterprises
Index slumped 5.7 percent, led by Ping An Insurance Group Co.,
China’s second-biggest insurance company by market value.
Benchmark stock indexes fell more than 1.5 percent in  Russia ,
 India , Hungary and Poland.  European finance ministers meeting today will grapple with
how to shield banks from the debt crisis and mull a further
boost to the region’s rescue fund. A Chinese purchasing
managers’ index, released by HSBC Holdings Plc and Markit
Economics last week, showed a third month of contraction. A
report today is forecast to signal U.S. factories probably grew
at the slowest pace since July 2009.  “Even though we are still far from 2008/09 lows,
investors’ confidence seems almost as fragile as back then,”
analysts at BNP Paribas SA including Bartosz Pawlowski in
London, said in an e-mailed note. “ China  is closed for its
week-long National Day holidays, but that didn’t deter markets
from taking a pessimistic view of markets.”  Greece   Today was the original target for approving an 8 billion-
euro ($11 billion) loan payment to Greece, the sixth installment
of a 110 billion-euro lifeline put together in May 2010. The
decision was pushed back until mid-October as Greece seeks to
repair its finances.  The Greek government said yesterday it approved 6.6 billion
euros of austerity measures.  The ruble depreciated 0.6 percent against the dollar and
the won weakened by 1.6 percent. The lira fell 0.3 percent after
Turkish exports grew at the slowest pace in eight months and
inflation decelerated, prompting speculation the central bank
will cut rates.  OTP Bank Nyrt., Hungary’s biggest lender, fell 4.1 percent
on concern Hungarian municipalities will default on debt. The
BUX Index, in which OTP has a 25 percent weighting, retreated
1.6 percent.  The Markit iTraxx SovX CEEMEA Index of eastern European,
 Middle East  and Africa credit-default swaps rose nine basis
points to 363, according to data provider CMA.  Bonds  The extra yield investors demand to own emerging-market
debt over U.S. Treasuries rose four basis points, or 0.04
percentage point, to 469, according to  JPMorgan Chase & Co. (JPM) ’s
EMBI Global Index.  The WIG20 Index fell 2 percent in Warsaw.  Russia’s Micex Index declined 1.6 percent and the FTSE/JSE
Africa All Shares Index slid 0.7 percent in Johannesburg.  Tupras Turkiye Petrol Rafinerileri AS (TUPRS) , Turkey’s sole
refiner, jumped 3.9 percent in Istanbul. The price of oil fell
by 0.8 percent in  New York . Turkey’s  ISE National 100 Index (XU100)  rose
less than 0.1 percent, the only major emerging-market bourse in
positive territory.  Ping An Insurance Group Co. tumbled 13 percent in Hong Kong
trading, while  Agile Property Holdings Ltd. (3383) , which develops
properties in Guangdong province, sank 18 percent.  China
Overseas Land & Investment Ltd. (688) , a developer controlled by the
nation’s construction ministry, dropped 11 percent.  Indonesia’s  Jakarta Composite Index (JCI)  slid 5.6 percent and
the SET Index retreated 5.1 percent in Bangkok.  The TAIEX Index slid 2.9 percent in Taipei.  HTC Corp. (2498) , which derived 83 percent of its 2010 revenue
from America and  Europe , dropped 3.2 percent.  Acer Inc. (2353) , which
got 63 percent of its revenue from  North America  and Europe in
2010, slumped 4.9 percent.  Markets in China and  South Korea  were closed for a holiday.  To contact the reporters on this story:
